doc.ContractDescription: THIS RESEARCH SEEKS TO UNDERSTAND AND DOCUMENT THE CULTURAL DEVELOPMENT AND EFFECTS OF PAST HUMAN SETTLEMENT IN THE DESERT ENVIRONMENT OF THE NORTH COAST OF PERU. THE PROPOSED RESEARCH WILL BE CONDUCTED BY DR. WILLIAM SATURNO, BOSTON UNIVERSITY, PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATOR, AND DR. TOM SEVER, UNIVERSITY OF ALABAMA IN HUNTSVILLE, CO-INVESTIGATOR. THIS RESEARCH WILL PROVIDE INSIGHT INTO THE DYNAMICS ASSOCIATED WITH THE DEVELOPMENT AND COLLAPSE OF COMPLEX SOCIETIES IN THIS AREA, INCLUDING MAPPING THE ELABORATION OF INFRASTRUCTURE ASSOCIATED WITH THEIR EXPANSION AND HELPING TO RESOLVE THEIR CHRONOLOGY. THE INCA ARE AMONG THE BEST-DOCUMENTED INHABITANTS OF ANCIENT PERU. YET, THEIR CULTURE WAS PRECEDED BY MANY CIVILIZATIONS THAT INHABITED LARGE REGIONS OF THE ANDEAN LANDSCAPE, BUT REMAIN RELATIVELY POORLY UNDERSTOOD. FOREMOST OF THESE WERE THE MOCHE WHO LIVED IN THE COASTAL DESERT VALLEYS FROM CA. 200 - 800 A.D. AND THE SUBSEQUENT CHIMU. DESPITE AN INCREASE IN THE NUMBER OF ARCHAEOLOGICAL INVESTIGATIONS INTO THESE GROUPS OVER LAST ONE HUNDRED YEARS, MANY COMPONENTS OF THE MOCHE AND CHIMU CIVILIZATIONS REMAIN UNKNOWN. THE PROPOSED RESEARCH WILL USE NASA REMOTE SENSING PRODUCTS AND FIELD-BASED INVESTIGATIONS TO LOCATE UNRECORDED ARCHAEOLOGICAL FEATURES RELATED TO THESE CULTURES. LANDSAT, HYPERION, ADVANCED LAND IMAGER (ALI), ADVANCED SPACEBORNE THERMAL AND EMISSIVITY RADIOMETER (ASTER), AND IN-HOUSE IKONOS DATA WILL BE USED TO IDENTIFY AND MAP ARCHAEOLOGICAL SITES AND THEIR RELATIONSHIPS TO ECOLOGICAL FEATURES IN ORDER TO BETTER UNDERSTAND ANCIENT ENVIRONMENTAL ADAPTATIONS AND CULTURAL INTERACTIONS IN THE REGION. THIS PROJECT WILL COLLABORATE WITH THE MAGDALENA DE CAO VIEJO PROJECT, DIRECTED BY DR. JEFFREY QUILTER, HARVARD UNIVERSITY, TO EXPLORE THE MOCHE AND CHICAMA VALLEYS. THE ANALYTICAL TECHNIQUES DISCOVERED IN PREVIOUS NASA RESEARCH PROJECTS FOR LOCATING ANCIENT SITES AND FEATURES WILL BE EXPANDED UPON AND APPLIED TO NORTHERN PERU TO DEMONSTRATE THE UTILITY OF REMOTE SENSING FOR ARCHAEOLOGICAL RESEARCH, INVENTORY, AND CULTURAL RESOURCE MANAGEMENT IN A DESERT REGION. THE RESULTING INFORMATION WILL FACILITATE MORE COMPREHENSIVE INTERPRETATIONS OF HUMAN SETTLEMENT IN THE REGION, PRIORITIZE AREAS FOR EXCAVATION, AND IMPROVE INVENTORIES OF CULTURAL RESOURCES FOR ARCHAEOLOGICAL AND HERITAGE MONITORING, MANAGEMENT, AND PROTECTION.
